      VALUES ("First of all Pandas are sexy, but aside from that there are other benefits of playing with Panda. You are a great team player, simply from the whole arsenal of disables that we possess. Also our tanking ability should never be over looked. Also for those who enjoy a challenge, Panda is one of those heroes that actually takes practicing to get great at, however for the newer players it doesn’t take much to be good with Panda.<br/>The advantages of playing Panda are that you can fit in a ton of niches. It really depends on what your team needs. If your team lacks a good disabler, becoming a semi-caster/tank is a very viable option, however if your team really lacks some sort of a carry type hero, we can do that just as well.", "Rune Control. It is a very vital part of early game. Since we are melee... and not exactly a harasser you should try and go for the side lanes. You don't have to solo, going with a partner is actually nice since you can land some easy kills early game. Try to go with the int nukers since you can be their meat shield while they destroy everything. BE AGGRESSIVE! I know you can be a decent late game hero, but early game you are a very decent threat to your opponents.  Many people get carried away, when they are higher leveled and have more HP, so they think they can pick on the panda. Let's see one unlucky cow that tried it. Mana management is a crucial part of a good Panda player. Since our mana pool is so limited, we need to use every last drop of our mana available. ", "Yes, Mid game is normally the time when most Ganks (Going around and Killing) occur.This is the time period that decides if your heroes are going to even make it to late game. If your team has a horrible mid game, chances are your late game isn't going to get better. Also due to the fact that Panda isn't exactly a h@xz00r late gamer, we need this mid game to be successful. In order for this to happen, we need to perfect using our ulti. Thus good good chunk of this Mid Game is based on how to use our awesome ultimate. There is a general misconception with Panda's ulti. Most people only use it for escape and rarely use it for any other purpose. This is probably because they don't really get a chance to use all of Panda's skill to it's maximum potential, with the short time period allowed. That is what I will try and do for you here today, to educate you on using your ulti for, killing, chasing, tanking, supporting, disabling, and escaping. <br/>Now I know it's not always possible to tell which way you are facing and such, but this is still very useful. For example, when you are chasing someone down the river you are moving South East and thus Storm will be highlighted first. Now, if you knew this information you can  simply press 'c' and cyclone the guy, however if you didn't then you would have to look and maybe, if you panic, even tab a few times before you get the right key going. Knowing which panda will be highlighted first can save you precious seconds, that the animation of your ulti wasted. ", "Always remember, our mid game was spectacular,  'our' late game is just as good. However we are not built to be the insane late game carry hero. That is why at this point, try and end the game earlier by killing, pushing, and then some more killing, pushing.<br/> AFTER you have split there is a definite procedure you should follow to escape successfully and deal damage back at the same time. The key concept here is actually just repeating the obvious, make ONLY your earth panda run. Leave the other two to duke it out with your opponents.<br/>At this stage of the game, mana should not be too much of a concern. When are are about level 15ish, remember that Blink Dagger Costs Mana. You have to add that to your combo. Or else you might end up blinking in, clap and have no mana left for your ulti. Other than that, mana is less strict as of now. ", "Go Go Awesome Warrior of Awesome", "dotastrategy", "http://www.dotastrategy.com/strategy-25532-GoGoAwesomeWarriorofAwesomenessByFlodian.html#skillbuild", "Brewmaster", "75");
