      VALUES ("Chen’s potential as a hero-killer has been overlooked by many. He’s an underestimated hero - something you can use to your advantage. According to me a hybrid battle-support Chen is the best way to go. Most people play Chen as a pure support hero - this causes him to become a soft target in battles. During ganks, he has hardly anything to contribute apart from his slow when played as a support; once dead, his valuable heal - a deciding factor - is removed. Remember, microing is an integral part of Chen’s gameplay; if you’re not too good at microing, you might want to practice against AI opponents until you get used to it. In this guide, I hope to teach you how I play Chen and to overcome all the above-said obstacles - have fun reading!", "Jungle: Probably the most important section out of the whole guide. Jungling is essential if you want to be a good Chen player. Jungling is advantageous to your team, too, becuase it can give an extra hero a solo lane. But Chen shouldn't only jungle. A good Chen will coordinate with his team mates and frequently pop out of the forest for ganks. To start with, head to a strong creep camp, such as Furbolgs or Centaurs. Dominate the strongest creep in that camp and kill the rest of the units in the camp, optionally using the creep's skill to quickly clear out the camp so that it recieves as little damage as possible. Once that creep is done, move on to the weakest camp, and clear it out. Your creep should have about half its HP left, so move on to the strongest camp again. In this camp, begin to attack the weaker units first, allowing your unit to tank the damage. Once your unit dies, Persuade the strongest creep in that camp, and repeat the cycle.<br/>Ganking: Usually, begin the gank by coming from behind the enemy so that he has nowhere to run, and it gives more time to position your creeps. Centaur Khan->hoof stomp, Ursa Warrior-> Thunder Clap, Dark Troll Warlord-> Ensnare", "Jungling: In middle game, you should try to jungle as much as possible, but should never give up an opportunity to gank an enemy. Constant ganking is essential if your team is to win, so you might have to ease up on jungling a little. Also, pushing becomes important, so jungling will have to take a back seat.<br/>Ganking: Ganking now shouldn't be much different than in early game. Just follow the 3 easy steps. However, several things also differ now: 1. You will have more creeps to control, meaning you need to know how to micro properly. 2. Both allies and enemies are getting stronger, meaning carries will begin to show their potential. 3. If you are dominating the game, enemies might start looking for you or focus firing you in ganks. After all, your Hand Of God is precious. <br/>As always, coordination with allies while ganking is a must. Time the use of both Mekansm and Hand Of God properly. Don't use them both in quick succession, unless you or your allies are very low on HP. ", "Pushing: Continue pushing as in mid game, but be more aware of you being the target of ganks. Be very map-aware, and wards can help a lot. Remember to Persuade the right creeps while pushing - a Ghost is pretty useless here. Use the abilities of your units effectively to clear out creep waves fast.<br/>Ganking: Ganking is very straightforward. As soon as you finish Guinsoo, use it as much as possible in your ganks. Always remember to use it on the pesky permabasher or a hero with a steroid spell (Eg: Barathrum) and finish them off before they can demolish your team. You can give up jungling all together, and roam the map to try and gank as much as possible. As before, remember to time the usage of Hand Of God and Mekansm properly. Notice, in the previous sequence, how I didn't use them simultaneously. If I did, Ursa would have killed me. Once you complete Guinsoo, there's not much more you need to farm for, so you can continue to supply your team with wards if you feel like. Aplha Wolves: The Alpha Wolf gives a great 30% increase damage Aura, which is extremely useful later on in the game, when heroes' damage get very high. Mortred, Juggernaut and the like, who are known for Criticals, will benefit a lot late game from this awesome aura. It's also useful in pushing and taking towers down fast. Vengeful's Level 4 Command Aura only gives 36% increase damage.", "Fear the Holy Knight", "dotastrategy", "http://www.dotastrategy.com/strategy-24582-FearTheHolyKnight.html#earlygame", "Chen", "75");
