      VALUES ("Looking at these stats you would think Invoker is just a spellcaster who can't have any carry potential right? Wrong. His spells ARE his carrying potential. Mid solo is his best lane, in any given situation or build. You can also put AA or ES or another hero to harrass with him mid, but thats not what this guide talks about.", "CS. Thats all you should be worried about. If they are fragile with short range you can harass them, but don't stray from your objective. Invoker has enough damage with exort that you should not even be trying to go for runes by using lane equilibrium, but to make sure you get every deny and creep kill possible. That brings us to lane equilibrium.<br/>Lane Equilibrium : Using either coordinated attacks, auto attacking or using spells that make your opponent get closer to the tower and therefore gives them the option of losing out on exp or running for the rune. Invoker is not one of those heroes because he is not a great ganker nor is he a bottle hero.<br/>Early lane mindset: If your team has vent or mic, this is VERY useful. If you are doing well enough that you can grab Sunstrike instead of coldsnap, keep an eye out on the map. Getting one or two kills globally will give you a huge advantage. Having a prophet and invoker is a very annoying combo, it guarantees another nuke from across the map which will usually spell out a death for the enemy. The reason why you want the team to be telling you when to Sunstrike is that you don't want to lose concentration on the lane, you will miss denies and csing while trying to micromanage.", "This is where the game gets tricky, you need some quick fingers to make use of Invoker really well here.<br/>Given the skill build, you should be able to dish out 2 spells at once, with a level 2-3 ultimate to swap through the spells in a cycle. You should have most of your 'core' items available to you, although BoT can always be replace with either phase boots or treads, and ultimate stick will take a little more time to acquire.<br/>At this time, you should be able to throw down 4 spells. Here's a quick spell rotation outline:<br/> Initiation with disable and damage: Tornado/EMP -> Def blast and metor<br/>Damage output: Fire spirits/ Alactricity -> Cold snap and def blast<br/>Turtling: Ghost walk/Ice wall -> def blast and EMP (walk up invisible behind opponents to do this)<br/>Long range: Tornado + Sunstrike", "There is not too much to say about this phase of the game, if you've got yourself here chances are you either failed or steam rolled with invoker. On rare occasions invokers do mediocre. So here are some pointers:<br/>Don't get ultimate level 4: If you've got ultimate stick in hand, 4 seconds is plenty of room to be ready for another set of spells. Unless you are very pro and have jackie chan hitting those keys for you, 2 seconds is an overkill.<br/>Make sure you're not getting interrupted: Use a black king bar, a linken's sphere or map awareness and positioning to dish out all of your spells. Most of invoker's abilities can be cast from a safe distance, and he's going to be the first target people attack.<br/>USE ALL YOUR SPELLS!: This is not said enough. Obviously you don't want to lose out on DPS by trying to change your spells, but there are right ways to use everything without wasting time and mana.<br/>Spell rotation late game should always look like this: Nado+ EMP -> Def Blast+ Meteor -> Summons+Alactricity -> Cold Snap+Ice wall<br/>Keep your distance. If you've got some initiation on your team this rotation will bring so much chaos that they won't know where to go. Even with a pushing team, this makes sure your opponents aren't patiently waiting behind a tower. USE force staff to get someone out and kill them quick, throw down your spells so they either choose to get hit along with the hero you pulled in, or watch them die.", "Versatile Invoker Build", "dota2-builds", "http://www.dota2-builds.com/view-dota2-build.php?hero=Invoker&id=259", "Invoker", "50");
