      VALUES ("Slardar is a decent hero from start to end. Slardar is powerful even without his cores. Slardar can almost fit in any role for the team. Slardar can swim in water. Slardar has a badass trident thing. Slardar has smexy gills. Slardar slithers leaving awesome tracks on the ground!<br/>In this guide, we will be playing a semi-carry and semi-ganking Slardar.", "Farm and Survive. Early game least important part of Slardar's game. Do not tower dive. Do not spam Crush, use your Crush strategically to get the most out of it. Try to harass, in order to strike fear in your enemy. Killing should never be your number one priority. Focus on your farming to ensure a good mid game later.", "Farming was your aim in early game, in mid game you should focus more on ganking with each level increase. Ganking during mid game is the most critical part of Slardar's role in the whole game. At earlier stages, you may have to the gank with the help of several allies. As you farm up your cores, you will be able to kill enemies solo. The semi-carry build is considered one of the best and cheap, and most effective for Slardar. It is focused on ‘burst’ damage, where your enemy takes in huge damage under a really short time and would be dead before you know it. Its par excellence together with a lifesteal item. <br/>You farmed in early game, let me stress again, you need to gank in mid game. It is your job. For a Slardar with MoM+AoM:<br/>1. Cast AD on the target (or after Slardar used Crush).<br/>2. Activate Sprint.<br/>3. Activate AoM.<br/>4. Charge in.<br/>5. Activate Avatar while charging in, if you have BKB.<br/>6. Use Crush when you are in range.<br/>7. Activate MoM. (you don't activate before you charge in because it cancels your Sprint)<br/>8. Whack the crap out of the sucker.", "If you had fun in mid game, you are gonna adore late game. What is left to do? After you achieved all your cores, you starting pushing into the enemy base. Most of the towers should have been destroyed already and only the Lv3 towers are left, so single hero pushes will not work. You need 3 or more allies, in order to mass push into the enemy base. So when your team calls a push, you should be in it. Often in pushes, the enemy team will try to stop you. And so there will also be several enemy heroes to stop your push. They may be hiding and waiting for a chance to initiate, or, it could be your team who is waiting to initiate. Heroes will start hiding behind the trees and then, when opportunity arises, one hero jumps out to attack another. Everybody who was hiding all comes out, resulting in a very messy battlefield, known as a clash. A clash is decisive of which team gets to push. A clash is ‘won’ when whichever team kills the most of or all of enemy heroes. Basically, when most enemy heroes are eliminated, it gives your team a breathing space to push without any interruptions, and that safety feeling as you will have close to no chance of getting killed until those death timers run out. So, after a team wins a clash, they will almost immediately begin pushing and uses this time to the maximum. A clash is decisive of which team gets to push. A clash is ‘won’ when whichever team kills the most of or all of enemy heroes. Basically, when most enemy heroes are eliminated, it gives your team a breathing space to push without any interruptions, and that safety feeling as you will have close to no chance of getting killed until those death timers run out. So, after a team wins a clash, they will almost immediately begin pushing and uses this time to the maximum.", "By Ebb and Flow", "dotastrategy", "http://www.dotastrategy.com/strategy-33292-ByEbbandFlowASlardarGuide.html#herooverview", "Slardar", "50");
