      VALUES ("Barathrum is a strong DPS hero with limited tanking capabilities. His main role in a team is DPS ganker and carry. His array of skills along with the right items make him a very dangerous hero in any one vs one situation. Barathrum's main advantage throughout the whole game is his high damage gained from Empowering Haste, and his permabashing capability from Greater Bash. It is important to make the most out of his huge damage and increase his DPS proficiency in the best way possible. SInce Barathrum already has a huge damage gain from his skills, it is more beneficial for him to buy IAS (Increase Attack Speed) items rather than damage items. <br/>Despite his huge damage advantage over other heroes, Barathrum's main weakness is his lack of AOE, range, or nuke of any sort. His early game can be very tough when laned against heroes with half-decent lane control. Barathrum is also very weak against nukes and disables. His potential to dish out massive amounts of damage make him a primary target for enemy disables, rendering him useless. For these reasons, Barathrum is almost never seen in leagues or professional play. So you may ask, 'Why should I pick Barathrum, when there are so many cons to his game?' Well the answer is, Barathrum has plenty of potential to be a DPS monster, especially in public play. When used right, Barathrum can be a very dangerous foe, and an unstoppable carry", "This is the part of the game when you are the most vulnerable. Since you don't have any range, nukes, harrassing skills or any AOE spells, your early game is going to be pretty brutal if your enemy knows what he is doing. It's very important at this stage that you stay away from danger and avoid being harrassed too much. Bring lots of regen consumables, and avoid being killed at all costs. If you are finding it hard to farm, then do a creep pull once in a while. Make sure that you do not get sent back to the fountain often because you really do need to level up fast to make the most of your gank potential.<br/>Learn to trigger creep aggro so you can get a clearer shot at the enemy creeps. You should almost always lane with a good babysitter, or an aggressive ally. Get the last hits and deny if you can. Assist in kills by using your Charge of Darkness to initiate and smash your enemies to death. Don't try to solo anyone if you think you might fail. If you happen to have come across a rune, abuse it and try to get First Blood. Haste synergizes very well with Empowering haste. Double Damage is very helpful as well. Invisibility should be given to an ally with a stun. Always pay attention to the minimap. Know when your enemies are missing and play it safe if you think they are coming to kill you. You don't have any reliable escape tools so the best method is to just avoid your gankers and tower hug. Remember, your main priority right now is to level up fast and farm for your items so that you can start ganking mid-game. If your early game performance is poor, chances are, it will handicap your mid game as well.", "This is the part of the game when you crawl out of your hole and starting getting into the action. Once you have your Bracers, Treads and MoM, you have the potential to solo gank lone heroes. Be cautious though, because at this point you are still very vulnerable to nukes and disables without a BKB. Heroes like Rhasta and Lion look weak and easy to kill, however they can unleash all their spells and kill you in an instant. Be wary during team battles because you are a primary target once you turn on your MoM.<br/>Ganking is the main part of Barathrum's mid game. Barathrum has potential to dish out massive amounts of damage while disabling the opponent at the same time with his Bash. Once you have your Mask of Madness, you will have sufficient IAS to permabash and kill most agility and intelligence heroes plus some strength heroes. You can manipulate Charge of Darkness by casting it from your fountain to a far away enemy. The mana regen from the fountain will refill your mana pool by the time you leave its regen range, thus you used no mana to cast your first charge. You should always ping your allies to let them know who you are charging, especially if you think you won't be able to kill the enemy by yourself.", "Late game is all about summing up how well you did in early and mid game. You reap the rewards of your earlier performance. For Barathrum, if you were able to gank successfully and got plenty of kills for your team, then late game should simply be wrapping it up. If you fed a lot and your opponents are much better farmed than you are, then your late game won't be as enjoyable. If you tried to gank a lot but left your opponent's carry to farm by himself for the whole game, then you will have a big problem to deal with.<br/>The most important aspect in late game is pushing. You win a game by destroying the opponent's Throne/Tree, simple enough. Most dota players tend to forget about the main objective and believe farming better items, or killing more heroes wins games. These two factors may play a huge role on deciding the winner, but the bottom line is: you win by pushing the enemy's towers. There are two general ways of pushing. One method is to simply go all out in one lane regardless of your enemy. This method is viable for heroes like Furion, Enigma, or Ezalor who actually can go all out in one lane because of their summons, or creep clearing skills. In this type of push, the enemy would not be able to counter push because they lack AOE damage and are overwhelmed by creeps or summons. While this method works to a limited degree of success, the second method is more practical. The second method is to gank and kill your opponents, then make a huge push that the opponent is very unlikely to recover from. This type of push fits Barathrum better because he is a ganker. Therefore, gank then push is the best way for Barathrum to finish a game.", "This ain't no milk cow", "dotastrategy", "http://www.dotastrategy.com/strategy-30967-ThisAintNoMilkCowAGuidebyDaMan2000.html", "Spirit Breaker", "80");
